<subSubSection id="35BB650AAE4DFF85FF77A560FEA007A5" pageId="1" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="7D1E3681AE4DFF85FF77A560FEA007A5" blockId="1.[151,1437,850,2028]" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="4FD5EA93AE4DFF85FF77A560FEC7000B" bold="true" box="[151,279,850,876]" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="BAA14D02AE4DFF85FEC5A560FDE0000C" authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="2008" box="[293,560,850,875]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Hoplitimyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inbioensis">
<emphasis id="4FD5EA93AE4DFF85FEC5A560FDE0000C" box="[293,560,850,875]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Hoplitimyia inbioensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="E59A2A04AE4DFF85FDA0A560FD54000B" box="[576,644,850,876]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="4.[151,269,1789,1813]" captionTargetBox="[159,1387,368,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-40@4.[159,1388,281,1721]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Hoplitimyia inbioensis, sp. nov., male holotype. 1, dorsal view. 2, lateral view. 3, lateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107270/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) differs from all other known 
<taxonomicName id="BAA14D02AE4DFF85FC0BA560FBA7000C" authorityName="James" authorityYear="1934" box="[1003,1143,850,875]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Hoplitimyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4FD5EA93AE4DFF85FC0BA560FBA7000C" box="[1003,1143,850,875]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Hoplitimyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except 
<taxonomicName id="BAA14D02AE4DFF85FB32A560FA4B000B" authority="James" authorityName="James" authorityYear="1979" box="[1234,1435,850,876]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Hoplitimyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taurina">
<emphasis id="4FD5EA93AE4DFF85FB32A560FA9C000C" box="[1234,1356,850,875]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">H. taurina</emphasis>
James
</taxonomicName>
in having scutellar spines that are at least 1.5 times as long as the scutellum. All other species have the spines at most subequal to the length of the scutellum, but in most taxa they are distinctly shorter. 
<taxonomicName id="BAA14D02AE4DFF85FAF0A59AFEDE008C" authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="2008" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Hoplitimyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inbioensis">
<emphasis id="4FD5EA93AE4DFF85FAF0A59AFEDE008C" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Hoplitimyia inbioensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="BAA14D02AE4DFF85FE17A5E0FDA5008C" authorityName="James" authorityYear="1979" box="[503,629,978,1003]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Hoplitimyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taurina">
<emphasis id="4FD5EA93AE4DFF85FE17A5E0FDA5008C" box="[503,629,978,1003]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">H. taurina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in general appearance, but is distinguished from it by having the scutellar spines directed posterodorsally in the same plane as the scutellum rather than being erect, and by having a vertical pale yellow band on the anterior part of the anepisternum (
<figureCitation id="E59A2A04AE4DFF85FBFEA21AFB5F0725" box="[1054,1167,1064,1090]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="4.[151,269,1789,1813]" captionTargetBox="[159,1387,368,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-40@4.[159,1388,281,1721]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Hoplitimyia inbioensis, sp. nov., male holotype. 1, dorsal view. 2, lateral view. 3, lateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107270/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Figs. 2, 3</figureCitation>
) that extends from the posterior edge of the anterior spiracle to the front coxa. This area is completely dark in 
<taxonomicName id="BAA14D02AE4DFF85FB41A261FACB070B" authorityName="James" authorityYear="1979" box="[1185,1307,1107,1132]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Hoplitimyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taurina">
<emphasis id="4FD5EA93AE4DFF85FB41A261FACB070B" box="[1185,1307,1107,1132]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">H. taurina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Also, the silvery vestiture of the abdominal tergites is brighter in 
<taxonomicName id="BAA14D02AE4DFF85FCC5A24FFC7007F1" authorityName="James" authorityYear="1979" box="[805,928,1149,1174]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Hoplitimyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taurina">
<emphasis id="4FD5EA93AE4DFF85FCC5A24FFC7007F1" box="[805,928,1149,1174]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">H. taurina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, composed of longer hairs, and is confined to tergites 2 and 3.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="35BB650AAE4DFF86FF26A2E0FE8D0785" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="1" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph id="7D1E3681AE4DFF85FF26A2E0FCE605F0" blockId="1.[151,1437,850,2028]" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="4FD5EA93AE4DFF85FF26A2E0FE8E078B" bold="true" box="[198,350,1234,1260]" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="4FD5EA93AE4DFF85FE92A2E1FE65078B" box="[370,437,1235,1260]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Male.</emphasis>
Head black, with lateral facial margin pale yellowish from about level of antenna ventrally, and yellowish in an area encompassing the suture between the face and oral sclerites, the latter with a black spot at the apex of the oral margin. Postocular orbit with very narrow yellowish coloration near middle. Sparse silvery pilosity present, especially evident on frons, face and genal region, longest on gena. Tomentum sparse, except on posterior surface of head where it is grayish, and along posterior margin of eye where there is a narrow silvery-white strip below middle. Antenna with scape very elongate (
<figureCitation id="E59A2A04AE4DFF85FB1AA39AFA9206A5" box="[1274,1346,1448,1474]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="4.[151,269,1789,1813]" captionTargetBox="[159,1387,368,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-40@4.[159,1388,281,1721]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Hoplitimyia inbioensis, sp. nov., male holotype. 1, dorsal view. 2, lateral view. 3, lateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107270/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), about two-thirds length of flagellum, slender but becoming slightly thicker apically, dark yellow becoming gradually brownish apically, and with very short, inconspicuous pilosity that is closely appressed to surface; pedicel and flagellum brownish black, pedicel with dark hairs especially evident near apex, flagellum with velvety vestiture. Labella shiny black, more brownish centrally in lateral view, sharply pointed apically, with very short, sparse pilosity. Palpus inconspicuous, pale yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D1E3681AE4DFF86FF26A09AFCB002ED" blockId="1.[151,1437,850,2028]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,152,1933]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">
Thorax (
<figureCitation id="E59A2A04AE4DFF85FECEA09AFEA605A5" box="[302,374,1704,1730]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="4.[151,269,1789,1813]" captionTargetBox="[159,1387,368,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-40@4.[159,1388,281,1721]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Hoplitimyia inbioensis, sp. nov., male holotype. 1, dorsal view. 2, lateral view. 3, lateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107270/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) dull black with postpronotal lobe, postalar callus, a narrow band on the anepisternum extending from the posterior margin of the anterior spiracle to the posterior margin of front coxa, tiny marking on the posterodorsal corner of the anepisternum, and the medial area of the laterotergite pale greenish yellow. Some small pleural regions, especially around sutures below the wing base, more brownish. Scutellum (
<figureCitation id="E59A2A04AE4DFF85FA8DA11AFF74040B" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="4.[151,269,1789,1813]" captionTargetBox="[159,1387,368,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-40@4.[159,1388,281,1721]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Hoplitimyia inbioensis, sp. nov., male holotype. 1, dorsal view. 2, lateral view. 3, lateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107270/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) entirely pale yellowish with posterior margin and spines vaguely brownish. Scutum with a mixture of appressed whitish and brownish pilosity, with two faint vittae on anterior 4/5 of presutural region. Pleura with generally distributed grayish white tomentum and whitish hairs on propleuron, posterior half of anepisternum, most of katepisternum, anterior two-thirds of anepimeron, and lateral half of laterotergite. Legs dark, dull yel- low with coxae and trochanters more brownish; basal half of front femur, basal half and dorsal part of middle femur, and much of hind femur more brownish, the darker areas appearing more shiny; tibiae vaguely darker on basal halves. Wing (
<figureCitation id="E59A2A04AE4EFF86FE53A6DFFE290260" box="[435,505,237,263]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="4.[151,269,1789,1813]" captionTargetBox="[159,1387,368,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-40@4.[159,1388,281,1721]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Hoplitimyia inbioensis, sp. nov., male holotype. 1, dorsal view. 2, lateral view. 3, lateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107270/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) slightly brownish with anterior portion dark brown, the dark area encompassing cells c, sc, br, bm, anterobasal part of cu 
<emphasis id="4FD5EA93AE4EFF86FD7AA72AFD790256" box="[666,681,280,305]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">p</emphasis>
, entire discal cell, r 
<subScript id="E12534C4AE4EFF86FC6FA71AFC470251" attach="left" box="[911,919,296,310]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">1</subScript>
, r 
<subScript id="E12534C4AE4EFF86FC50A71AFC190251" attach="left" box="[944,969,296,310]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">2+3</subScript>
, and anterior two-thirds of r 
<subScript id="E12534C4AE4EFF86FAF5A71AFAFF0251" attach="left" box="[1301,1327,296,310]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">4+5</subScript>
, with the brown coloration not quite reaching wing apex; dark areas of wing with distinct microtrichia, other areas bare. Vein R 
<subScript id="E12534C4AE4EFF86FF07A7B2FF3F02E9" attach="left" box="[231,239,384,398]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">4</subScript>
absent. Halter with knob pale green, stem brownish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D1E3681AE4EFF86FF26A7AFFACB0085" blockId="2.[151,1436,152,1933]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">
Abdomen (
<figureCitation id="E59A2A04AE4EFF86FEABA7AFFE4102D0" box="[331,401,413,439]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="4.[151,269,1789,1813]" captionTargetBox="[159,1387,368,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-40@4.[159,1388,281,1721]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Hoplitimyia inbioensis, sp. nov., male holotype. 1, dorsal view. 2, lateral view. 3, lateral view of head and antennae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107270" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107270/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) dull black, membrane in front of first tergite paler, extreme lateral margins of tergites and posterior margin of tergite 5 vaguely brownish, and lateral part of sutures between tergites 2–3, 3–4, and 4–5 very narrowly pale brown. Tergites with general vestiture of short, sparse, pale hairs; tergites 2 and 3 and anterior part of 4 with very dense grayish-silver tomentum covering most of surface (best seen with anterior lighting); remainder of tergite surfaces with inconspicuous dull tomentum that gives the abdomen a matte appearance. Sternites similar to tergites in color, but without silvery tomentum; posterior half of sternite 1 with a pale green band that narrows slightly at middle, anterior third or so of second sternite with greenish band that is widest medially, and posterior margin of sternite 3 and extremely narrow margin of sternite 4 pale greenish; lateral margin of tergite 4 and lateral and posterior margins of sternite 5 pale but not as conspicuously green. Gonocoxites with lateral margins evenly rounded (
<figureCitation id="E59A2A04AE4EFF86FC6BA52FFC030050" box="[907,979,797,823]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–7" captionStartId="5.[151,269,1811,1835]" captionTargetBox="[187,1399,183,1765]" captionTargetId="figure-49@5.[179,1408,174,1787]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 4–7. Hoplitimyia inbioensis, sp. nov., male terminalia of paratype. 4, genital capsule, dorsal view. 5, phallic complex, dorsal view. 6, epandrium and post-genitalic structures, dorsal view. 7, phallic complex, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107274" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107274/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); gonocoxal apodemes absent; apex of hypandrium rectangularly produced, slightly rounded posteriorly, very concave dorsally. Gonostylus displaced ventrally, triangularly produced on medial margin. Phallic complex (
<figureCitation id="E59A2A04AE4EFF86FBF1A541FBA400EA" box="[1041,1140,883,909]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–7" captionStartId="5.[151,269,1811,1835]" captionTargetBox="[187,1399,183,1765]" captionTargetId="figure-49@5.[179,1408,174,1787]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 4–7. Hoplitimyia inbioensis, sp. nov., male terminalia of paratype. 4, genital capsule, dorsal view. 5, phallic complex, dorsal view. 6, epandrium and post-genitalic structures, dorsal view. 7, phallic complex, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5107274" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5107274/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Fig. 5, 7</figureCitation>
) trifid, median lobe truncate posteriorly and slightly longer than lateral lobes, which are tapered posteriorly; attachment structure narrowed medially. Epandrium (
